In this main experiment, we tested two aspects of the voice quality: naturalness and accent quality tests.
The results are shown in Table 1. We also
present the data for the same speakers in US generated with the system
described in [12].
It can be seen from the table that the accent transfer quality is reasonably good (MOS score of 4 or higher).

We also validated if speaker characteristics were kept during the accent transfer process.
In particular, we checked this by analyzing news-style reading appropriateness and long-form naturalness.
The results are shown in Table 2, and the MOS scores
are perceived as good as well.
If we compare Table 1 and Table 2, we see that the short-form and long-form naturalness scores are close for most of the speakers in most cases.

One natural question is what loss in quality there is between the first Tacotron-based model and the final CHiVE-BERT model.
The comparison of accent transfer quality and style appropriateness between the
intermediate Tacotron model and the final CHiVE-BERT model are shown in
Tables 3 and 4
respectively.
As expected, training from synthetic data leads to some loss in quality.
However, the quality of the speech yielded by the final system is still high (above 4.0 in MOS).
